{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17500710","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17500710"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:16:32+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:16:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1663"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1663","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1663"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.04,0.15,0.23,0.57]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1663"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"42075"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1663","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1663"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1663"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"27050"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"441"},{"type":"tags","id":"1193"},{"type":"tags","id":"2096"},{"type":"tags","id":"4963"},{"type":"tags","id":"11636"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3735"},{"type":"contributions","id":"4268"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43983"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"42075","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/42075"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 63-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a 24-hour history of ocular discomfort and watery discharge from the left eye. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination she appears well. Ophthalmic exam demonstrates a visual acuity of 6/6 bilaterally and her intraocular pressures are within normal limits. Follicular conjunctival injection is noted on eversion of the upper left eyelid.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Acute angle closure glaucoma","Scleritis","Episcleritis","Blepharitis","Conjunctivitis"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EFollicular conjunctival injection is consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003Econjunctivitis\u003C/strong\u003E. The follicles are round traslucent collections of lymphocytes. Blood vessels pass over the top of these follicles, rather than within them. The most common cause of the conjunctivitis in this patient is a viral infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EViral conjunctivitis causes a non-purulent watery discharge whilst bacterial conjunctivitis has a yellowish thick discharge producing caking and crusting in the lashes. Infective conjunctivitis almost always becomes bilateral. Adenoviral infections are the commonest and often spread by health professionals failing to wash/sanitise their hands between consultations. These infections (adenoviral) often produce enlarged draining pre-auricular and sub-mandibular lymphadenopathy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute angle closure glaucoma\u003C/strong\u003E presents with significant eye pain, conjunctival infection, mid-dilated pupil, corneal oedema, raised intraocular pressures and evidence of glaucomatous optic neuropathy. The patient\u0027s presentation is not consistent with this.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EScleritis\u003C/strong\u003E can present with a \u0027red eye\u0027, however the pain is significantly worse than in conjunctivitis. Patients may complain that they are woken up at night with the pain or complain of pain with eye movements. On examination, a characteristic violet-bluish hue is seen with scleral oedema. Scleritis is associated with systemic autoimmune conditions including Granolomatosis with Polyangiitis, rheumatoid arthritis and Systemic lupus erythematosus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEpiscleritis\u003C/strong\u003E is an inflammation of the episcleral tissue overlying the sclera and is characterised by injection of the bulbar conjunctiva. This patient however has injection and follicles in the tarsal conjunctiva (under the upper eyelid). Episcleritis typically self resolves in two to three days.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlepharitis\u003C/strong\u003E is eyelid margin inflammation and is usually caused by Meibomian gland dysfunction and/or staphylococcal infection. Patients usually complain of redness, irritation and eyelid sticking. On examination, crusting, erythema and oedema can be seen at the eyelid margin with potential blocked Meibomian glands visualised on inspection of the posterior eyelid margin. This is not seen in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Follicular injection of the tarsal conjunctiva is associated with conjunctivitis."],"references":["Akpek EK, Thorne JE, Qazi FA, Do DV, Jabs DA. Evaluation of Patients with Scleritis for Systemic Disease. Ophthalmology 2004;111:501-506. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/15019326/","Akpek EK, Uy HS, Christen W, Gurdal C, Foster CS. Severity of episcleritis and systemic disease association. Ophthalmology. 1999;106:729. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/10201593/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"27050"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1663"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"27050","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/27050"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-01-30T12:10:59+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-01-30T12:10:59+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1663"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"42075"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","i